<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>VT-365 Diesel Engine Diagnostics (2002) - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEMS DIAGNOSTICS - Circuit Diagnostics -
        Engine Fan Control (EFAN)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
        <title>Engine Fan Control (EFAN)</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3369" filename="../figd33/d3369.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="472px"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for Engine Fan Control (EFAN)</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The Function Diagram for EFAN includes the following:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Control Module (ECM)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Engine Coolant Temperature (ECT) sensor</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Intake Air Temperature (IAT) sensor</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic System Controller (ESC)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Engine fan relay</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>Function</title>
            </para>
            <para>The EFAN control provides ON/OFF control of the engine cooling system fan. The ECM can be programmed
                to set and monitor limits for engine coolant temperature, intake air temperature, engine mode selection
                (operating or diagnostic).
            </para>
            <para>EFAN is accessible with the EST. Fan on and off temperature can be programmed by technician, but the
                mode of operation must be done by Tech Services.
            </para>
            <para>The purpose of the Engine Fan Control is to provide the correct logic to determine when the Fan should
                be turned on or off by energizing/de-energizing the fan drive relay. The purpose of the engine fan is to
                allow a higher air flow for heat exchange between the radiator and the ambient air when needed.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Engine Fan Control</emph>: This parameter indicates to the on-board electronics
                whether or not the truck has the electronic engine fan control feature.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">AC Fan Activation</emph>: This feature will allow fan activation though the ECM when
                requested through the ESC during AC operation.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Disable</emph>: Feature is turned off at all times.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Fan On Temperature</emph>: This parameter indicates the coolant temperature that the
                fan will be electronically activated.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Fan Off Temperature</emph>: This parameter indicates the coolant temperature that the
                fan will be electronically deactivated.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>EFAN Circuit Operation</title>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3370" filename="../figd33/d3370.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"/>
                <caption>EFAN Circuit Diagram</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>With the ignition key on, power is supplied to terminals 30 and 86 on the engine fan relay. Terminal
                X4-14 on the ECM is used to either apply or remove the ground circuit from the fan relay coil side
                terminal 85. When the fan needs to be energized (turned on), terminal X4-14 is set high (12 volts) and
                the ground circuit to the coil side of the relay is interrupted causing the relay to unlatch, sending
                power supply from terminal 30 to 87A on the relay to the fan clutch. When the fan needs to be
                de-energized (turned off), terminal X4-14 is set low (grounded internal to the ECM) and the ground
                circuit to the coil side of the relay is complete causing the relay to latch, interrupting the power
                supply to the fan clutch.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The circuit shown is with the fan engaged / on and the relay de-energized / off.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            </para>
            <para>An open or short to ground in the EFAN can be detected by the ECM during an on-demand engine standard
                test. The IAT and ECT are monitored continuously. If a DTC is detected in the IAT or ECT, the EFAN
                control is disabled and the engine fan is on all the time.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Before diagnosing, check that ECM is programmed correctly. Verify vehicle / application has an
                        electronic fan.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <title>EFAN Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs)</title>
            </para>
            <para>DTCs are read using the Electronic Service Tool (EST) or by counting the flashes from the amber and
                red ENGINE lamp.
            </para>
            <verbatim id="f240dtc246">
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">DTC 246</emph>
                </line>
                <line>
                    <emph type="bold">OCC self test fault</emph>
                </line>
            </verbatim>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>DTC 246 is set by the ECM only during the Key ON Engine OFF Standard test. During this test
                        the ECM performs an output circuit test that momentarily enables the EFAN solenoid and measures
                        the voltage drop across the relay
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Tools</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Electronic Service Tool (EST) with Master Diagnostics software</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>International&#174; EZ-Tech Interface Cable</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Digital Multimeter (DMM)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Relay breakout harness</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>EFAN Pin Point Diagnostics</title>
            <figure id="f24007" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic id="d3370" filename="../figd33/d3370.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"/>
                <caption>EFAN Circuit Diagram</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The EFAN circuit requires the use of vehicle circuit diagrams. See truck Chassis Electrical Circuit
                Diagram manual for circuit numbers, connector and fuse locations.
            </para>
            <table id="te24007037" tblwidth="pg-wide" frame="topbot">
                <tgroup cols="3">
                    <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="2.00in"/>
                    <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="0.86in"/>
                    <colspec colname="col3" colwidth="3.00*"/>
                    <spanspec namest="col1" nameend="col3" spanname="SPAN1"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Voltage / Resistance Checks</emph>
                                    (Disconnect fan clutch. Key ON Engine OFF.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>Test Point</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>Spec</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Comments</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>A to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>B+</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Do Output State Test High. If B+ is present, the EFAN circuit is functioning. If
                                    no voltage is present, the relay is not on. Check for an open in circuit to solenoid
                                    or improperly programmed ECM.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry>
                                <para>A to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>0V</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>Do Output State Test Low. If voltage is present, check for short to voltage source
                                    or actuator circuit shorted to ground.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>B to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Key OFF resistance to ground. If >5&#x2126;, check for open or loose connection to
                                    ground at engine crankcase.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Voltage Checks at Fan Relay Connector</emph>
                                    (Check with relay removed and key ON.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>30 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>B+</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3" morerows="1">
                                <para>V
                                    <subscript>IGN</subscript>
                                    power to relay. If no voltage is present, see truck Chassis Electrical Circuit
                                    Diagram manual.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>86 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>B+</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry>
                                <para>-</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>85 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>0V</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>ECM control (no voltage expected)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>87A to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>0V</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Power to EFAN (no voltage expected with relay disconnected)</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Voltage Checks at ECM X4</emph>
                                    (Check with breakout box installed to ECM and chassis harness, relay installed, and
                                    key ON.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-14 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>0V</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Fan off - Do Output State Test Low</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-14 to gnd</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>B+</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>Fan on - Do Output State Test High</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colspan="3" spanname="SPAN1">
                                <para>
                                    <emph type="bold">Harness Resistance Checks</emph>
                                    (Turn ignition key OFF. Disconnect fan. Check with breakout box installed on chassis
                                    harness only.)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>X4-14 to 85</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If >5&#x2126;, check for harness open between ECM and relay terminal.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>87A to A (fan)</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If >5&#x2126;, check for harness open between relay terminal and A (fan).</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>30 to Fuse</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If >5&#x2126;, check for harness open between fuse and relay terminal. See truck
                                    Chassis Electrical Circuit Diagram manual for fuse information.
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <entry colname="col1">
                                <para>30 to 86</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col2">
                                <para>&#60;5&#x2126;</para>
                            </entry>
                            <entry colname="col3">
                                <para>If >5&#x2126;, check for harness open at relay terminal.</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
